Text: Scientific study and scrutiny tell us that these vaccines are safe and extremely effective, not only at lowering your risk of getting the virus, but also at preventing severe cases that require hospitalization.

For over a year our country and the world have been combatting a global pandemic unprecedented in our lifetimes. We’ve completely changed how we work, play, and celebrate. This week, at long last, every American adult is eligible to receive a vaccine against this deadly virus.

As we close out Black Maternal Health Week I am thinking of all the incredible care workers trying to make a difference right now. We need to recruit more to the maternal health workforce, and give them the tools they need to provide more access and better care. #BMHW21

It is an incredible achievement that next week vaccine availability will open to most Americans, but we know that members of vulnerable communities are still trying to get appointments. If you can, please help them get appointments as soon as possible.

It has been 13 years to the day since the then worst-ever mass shooting at Virginia Tech, and the federal government has not done anything to prevent these tragedies. 

It is far past time for us to act — to do nothing is to be complicit.

We’ve also taken a historic step towards justice by providing more than $5 billion in debt relief & assistance to Black farmers who have faced longstanding discrimination & worse outcomes during the pandemic.
We’ve expanded the EITC & Child Tax Credit, food assistance, UI & the child care tax credit—together, we’ll reduce Black poverty by 37% this year. For black children, poverty will be cut 54%.

The bill also includes a provision based on my MOMMIES Act to help prevent maternal deaths. It also expands access to health coverage, behavioral health care & funding to get vaccines to all Americans.

The pandemic has devastated communities of color and placed a harsh light on existing systemic inequities. To address the health impacts of COVID-19, the bill will send $7.6 billion to community health centers, $3.3 billion for the Indian Health Service, $50 million for Title X. https://t.co/30tQeAqwri

After a year in lockdown, we still have a long road ahead — millions of at risk Americans still need vaccines, businesses across the country are struggling to stay afloat, and too many of us are mourning someone we've lost. This plan puts on a path to get out of this crisis.

I’m grateful for all Matt has done for the people of New Jersey & for our country. He's helped improve the lives of countless Americans—and he's just getting started.

Please join me in congratulating @mattklapper on the next step of his journey to help fulfill America’s promise.

Of course, I’m grieving Matt’s departure. Over the years, he's become my brother. He’s someone who I’ve relied on during our toughest challenges. He’s built and led an incredible, diverse and inclusive team in the Senate—to say he’ll be missed is an understatement.

Matt is the rare leader who can build coalitions & who has the integrity, intellect & grit to always do what’s right & make a difference. He's going to do great things at DOJ & continue the fight for social, racial & economic justice. I’m excited for him, AG Garland & our nation.

21 years ago, a young @MattKlapper joined me on a mission to advance civil rights & opportunity. After decades in the trenches & years as my chief of staff, Matt joined DOJ in January—with today’s confirmation, he'll officially serve as AG Garland's COS. I'm so proud of him. https://t.co/94c8xIhds2
